                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d366">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">724.3415/3830: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Secretary of State</gloss> to the
                        Minister in Bolivia</hi> (<persName type="to">
                        <hi rend="italic">Des Portes</hi>
                    </persName>)</head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1934-06-20T11:00:00-04:00"
                            >June 20, 1934—11 a.m.</date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>6. Your telegram 35, June 14, 11 a.m. You may inform the Foreign Minister that
                    the President’s Proclamation May 28 does not of course apply to sales completed
                    before the issuance of the Proclamation, and that there have been excepted from
                    the prohibitions of the Proclamation goods manufactured and ready for delivery
                    prior to May 28, 1934, pursuant to valid and binding contracts of sale entered
                    into prior to that date and which had been paid for in whole or in part by the
                    belligerent government. The Bolivian Minister has been officially apprised of
                    the foregoing.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Hull</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
